As an American, we have our own problems in history. What was done the Native Americans, while seldom, if ever, referred to as genocide by our own history books, was genocide in and of itself. Sometimes it was intentional. Sometimes it was by proximity. Its burden was split across countless groups of perpetrators. The bottom line was, however, that millions of a people we had no regard for ended up dead, and we did very little, if often times, anything, to stop it. It's nothing something anyone wants on their country's record, and it's not something people alive today, who had no way of either aiding or stopping the event, should explicitly be blamed for. The past is the past. If people today can agree that the Armenian relocation was a disaster, be it intentional or otherwise, then we can agree that there's a few things we can learn from it, and hopefully how to avoid similar losses of life today.

